\paragraph{Context}
Linear multistep methods for ODEs are given in two notations: the $[\alpha,\beta]$ formulation and the traditional $(\rho,\sigma)$ formulation. The order condition follows from Taylor expansions of the method's difference equation, relating it to the generating polynomials evaluated at $e^{z}$.

Variables:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\alpha$: generating polynomial $\alpha(z)=\alpha_k z^k+\alpha_{k-1}z^{k-1}+\dots+\alpha_0$
    \item $\beta$: generating polynomial $\beta(z)=\beta_k z^k+\beta_{k-1}z^{k-1}+\dots+\beta_0$
    \item $\rho$: characteristic polynomial $\rho(z)=\alpha_k z^k+\alpha_{k-1}z^{k-1}+\dots+\alpha_0$
    \item $\sigma$: second characteristic polynomial $\sigma(z)=\beta_k z^k+\beta_{k-1}z^{k-1}+\dots+\beta_0$
    \item $p$: order of the method
\end{itemize}

Referenced equation:
\begin{equation}
\alpha(e^{-z})-z\beta(e^{-z})=C_0+C_1z+C_2z^2+\cdots
\tag{410c}
\end{equation}
